utional Washington journalism, he apologized and committed himself to a lis=
tening tour=E2=80=94an attempted reset, or in <i>Post </i>corporate pablum,=
 a chance to <i>fix it</i>.<br/><br/>In any event, Auletta seemed keen to t=
urn the screws, perhaps in part because Buzbee is a fellow Livingston judge=
=2E In his opening speech, he called at=
tention to a recent report in <b>Alan=20=
Rusbridger</b>=E2=80=99s <i>Prospect</i> highlighting the allegation that L=
ewis knew of, or was involved in, News Corp.=E2=80=99s decision to delete 3=
0 million emails and discard nine boxes of potential evidence relating to t=
he scandal. (In his prepared remarks, Auletta wrote that Murdoch did this t=
o =E2=80=9Ccover his ass=E2=80=9D; alas, that pithy locution didn=E2=80=99t=
 make it into the actual speech). He then called attention to Lewis=E2=80=
=99s alleged pressure campaigns against Buzbee and Folkenflik, stating, =E2=
=80=9CLewis doesn=E2=80=99t get a pass.=E2=80=9D (History rhymes, of course=
:
More than a decade ago, Auletta=E2=80=99s <i>New Yorker </i>column had been=
 the vehicle for <b>Jill Abramson</b>=E2=80=99s version of the events surro=
unding her own ouster from the <i>Times</i> under its then-new British C.E.=
O., <b>Mark Thompson</b>.) <br/><br/>The tone and tenor of Auletta=E2=80=99=
s critique conveyed the challenges now facing the <i>Post</i>=E2=80=99s pub=
lisher as he seeks to lead the paper out of its financial, editorial, and c=
ultural morass. The man initially seen as the <i>Post</i>=E2=80=99s potenti=
al savior has now become its latest scapegoat=E2=80=94which, as I noted las=
t week, may limit his ability to enact the strategic changes that are so <i=
>obviously</i> necessary. Indeed, a few beats later in his speech, Auletta =
actually <i>commended</i> Lewis for pressing his newsroom to =E2=80=9Crecog=
nize=E2=80=9D the =E2=80=9Creality=E2=80=9D of its current financial woes. =
(Here again, the written draft was more apt: He commended Lewis for injecti=
ng =E2=80=9Ca sense of alarm=E2=80=9D into the newsroom.) <br/><br/>After l=
ast week,
however, Lewis must now pull this off with the handicap of adhering to deco=
rum and appeasing the Livingston set=E2=80=94those who, in a fit of magical=
 thinking, expect <b>Jeff Bezos </b>to either fire Lewis (he won=E2=80=99t,=
 not for <i>this </i>anyway) or at least formalize the separation of church=
 and state between front office and newsroom. Alas, the tragedy here is tha=
t church and state need to work <i>more closely</i> together to close the $=
77 million hole on the <i>Post</i>=E2=80=99s P&amp;L. But that=E2=80=99s no=
t conventional wisdom in such circles. This week, former <i>Post </i>media =
columnist and <i>New York Times </i>public editor <b>Margaret Sullivan</b> =
called on Bezos to reinstate the role of the ombudsman=E2=80=94epitomizing =
the misalignment between journalists=E2=80=99 concerns and the existential =
business problems that <i>actually</i> bedevil the <i>Post</i>. This will n=
ot be the last such idea slipped into the public suggestion box, of course.=
<br/><br/>Regardless, Lewis got the memo. In an
internal meeting earlier this week, he was described to me as being =E2=80=
=9Cmore contrite.=E2=80=9D In private conversations with staff, he is said =
to be choosing his words more carefully. He is, it seems, being <i>less </i=
>direct. And he is leaving more of the day-to-day interfacing with the news=
room to his newly installed executive editor, <b>Matt Murray</b>, a very af=
fable guy and newsroom lifer whom reporters and editors seem to genuinely l=
ike and view as blameless for this shitshow. During these meetings, however=
, many staffers have expressed both concern over Murray=E2=80=99s successor=
, incoming editor <b>Rob Winnett</b>, and Murray=E2=80=99s future gig=E2=80=
=94running the <i>third newsroom</i>.<br/><br/>We=E2=80=99ll see if Lewis=
=E2=80=99s contrition is effective, but the whole penance tour raises a lar=
ger question. Inarguably, the challenges to existing business models call n=
ot for more decorum but for <i>greater </i>candor. Indeed, the urgency with=
 which he had initially diagnosed the <i>Post</i>=E2=80=99s
problems was actually his most refreshing characteristic. =E2=80=9CPeople a=
re <i>not reading your stuff</i>=E2=80=9D may have offended some high pries=
ts in the newsroom, but it was also inarguably true. And perhaps the fact t=
hat it offended some people says more about the <i>Post</i>=E2=80=99s cultu=
re than it does about Lewis, himself. <br/><br/>Anyway, one of the more dep=
ressing elements of this endlessly depressing incident is that Lewis, who e=
ntered the company by calling for transparency (<i>say it</i>, <i>fix it</i=
>, etcetera), must now do what so many other media leaders have done in the=
 past=E2=80=94pat his newsroom on the collective head while doing the ugly =
business of making the numbers work behind the scenes. It=E2=80=99s a recip=
e for mutual distrust and contempt, and it=E2=80=99s not like that $77 mill=
ion hole is going to be plugged by a listening tour.<br/></td>
         </tr>
